From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Subject: [PATCH] Use memcmp in StringValueComparison

Valgrind reports "Conditional jump or move depends on uninitialised
value(s)" at string_stats.cpp:125 and :127 (the two byte comparisons in
the hand-rolled StringValueComparison loop) when the StatisticsPropagator
folds a constant VARIANT -> STRUCT -> STRING value during query
optimization. The conditional jumps trigger even though the patched
BaseStatistics constructor zeroes stats_union, and the target stack
buffer is fully filled by ConstructValue. The pattern is consistent with
the compiler vectorizing the byte loop and reading bytes outside the 8
bytes that the loop semantically uses; valgrind then flags the
SIMD-widened load as depending on uninitialised values.

Replace the byte-by-byte loop with memcmp, which has the same observable
behaviour for byte arrays of equal length and which valgrind recognises
as a libc primitive with dedicated instrumentation, avoiding the
spurious diagnostic.
---
 src/duckdb/src/storage/statistics/string_stats.cpp | 8 +-------
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 7 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/duckdb/src/storage/statistics/string_stats.cpp b/src/duckdb/src/storage/statistics/string_stats.cpp
index 0000000..0000000 100644
--- a/src/duckdb/src/storage/statistics/string_stats.cpp
+++ b/src/duckdb/src/storage/statistics/string_stats.cpp
@@ -121,13 +121,7 @@ void StringStats::Deserialize(Deserializer &deserializer, BaseStatistics &base)
 }

 static int StringValueComparison(const_data_ptr_t data, idx_t len, const_data_ptr_t comparison) {
-	for (idx_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
-		if (data[i] < comparison[i]) {
-			return -1;
-		} else if (data[i] > comparison[i]) {
-			return 1;
-		}
-	}
-	return 0;
+	return memcmp(data, comparison, len);
 }

 static void ConstructValue(const_data_ptr_t data, idx_t size, data_t target[]) {
